{{Infobox storm | name = 1969 Cincinnati tornado outbreak | image = | alt = | caption = | formed = | active = August 9–10, 1969 | dissipated = | lowest pressure = | lowest temperature = | tornadoes = 10 | fujitascale = F3–F4 | tornado duration = | highest winds = | gusts = | maximum snow = | power outages = | total fatalities = 4–5 fatalities; 354 injured | damages = ≥$14.8 million in 1969 [[United States dollar|USD]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disastercenter.com/ohio/tornado.html|title=Ohio Tornadoes|first=Created by The Disaster Center: text, html and graphics by Christopher Effgen|last=build@alaska.net|website=www.disastercenter.com|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref> | affected = [[Indiana]], [[Ohio]], [[West Virginia]], [[Virginia]] | location = | current advisories = | enhanced = | notes = }}
The '''1969 Cincinnati tornado''' was a powerful, devastating and deadly [[tornado]] that struck [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] on Saturday, August 9, 1969, at 5:57pm.<ref name="significant">Grazulis, Thomas P. (1993). Significant Tornadoes 1680-1991: A Chronology and Analysis of Events. Environmental Films. pp.1107. Retrieved July 28, 2018</ref><ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/health/cincinnati-health-department-divisions1/public-health-preparedness/tornadoes/|title=Tornadoes|website=www.cincinnati-oh.gov|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref> The tornado was a [[Fujita scale|F3 or F4]] on the [[Fujita scale]]. (Most records show its official rating as F3, but some have as an F4 and its possible it may have caused F4 damage.) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/tornado/19690809.39.17|title=Tornado History Project: 19690809.39.17|website=www.tornadohistoryproject.com|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="short lived">Staff, Elizabeth Kane, Cincinnati Enquirer (April 3, 2004) [http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2004/04/03/tornadoes.pdf Tornadoes – short lived, but destructive]. ''www.enquirer.com''. Retrieved July 28, 2018</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QHXchdlu6xA|title=1969 Cincinnati F4 Tornado|first=|last=Jordan Plumbo|date=1 September 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref> Part of a larger outbreak of at least 10 tornadoes, mainly centered within [[Indiana]], the tornado caused at least 4 deaths and hundreds of injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/tornado/1969/8/9/table|title=Tornado History Project: August 9, 1969|website=www.tornadohistoryproject.com|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/tornado/1969/8/10/table|title=Tornado History Project: August 10, 1969|website=www.tornadohistoryproject.com|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="auto"/> It was the deadliest tornado in the state of Ohio that year (and made the outbreak it was in that year's deadliest in the state).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/tornado/Ohio/1969/table|title=Tornado History Project: Ohio in 1969|website=www.tornadohistoryproject.com}}</ref>
{{Tornado Chart |Total = 10 |FU = 0 |F0 = 3 |F1 = 1 |F2 = 4 |F3 = 2 |F4 = ? |F5 = 0 |Enhanced=no }}
==Event summary== {{Infobox storm | name = | image = | fujitascale = F3–F4 | tornado duration = | highest winds = | total fatalities = | damages = | location = | current advisories = | enhanced = | notes = }}
In the late afternoon hours of Saturday, August 9, the tornado formed in the Cincinnati suburb of Wyoming, 8 miles north-northeast of downtown Cincinnati. Moving east–southeast at 40–50mph,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.accuweather.com/index.php?showtopic=7074&st=480|title=Today in Weather History - AccuWeather.com Forums|website=forums.accuweather.com|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/abr/This_Day_in_Weather_History_Aug_09|title=This Day in Weather History: August 9th|first=US Department of Commerce, NOAA, National Weather|last=Service|website=www.weather.gov|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref> it traveled through the city's suburban neighborhoods of Hartwell and Roselawn, and the several of its northeastern suburbs, including Reading, Arlington Heights, Golf Manor, and Madeira.<ref name="short lived"/><ref name="noaa.gov">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180729081415/https://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/orders/IPS/IPS-83617A72-C33B-4303-B49F-8AA4C897CDBF.pdf]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nws.noaa.gov/os/tornado/survivors.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-07-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923021545/http://www.nws.noaa.gov/os/tornado/survivors.shtml |archive-date=2017-09-23 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> It carved a path through Hamilton and Clermont counties that was 22 miles long and up to 400 yards wide. It hit the communities of Milford and Perintown before finally dissipating north of Williamsburg.<ref name="short lived"/><ref name="noaa.gov"/>
All the death were in Hamilton County, including three members of one family.<ref name="significant"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KYn2iCsbT_A|title=1969 Cincinnati Tornado|first=|last=knirbneo|date=30 January 2011|publisher=|via=YouTube|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=http://historysstory.blogspot.com/2013/08/august-9-tornado-hits-cincinnati.html|title=Today in History: AUGUST 9 = Tornado Hits Cincinnati|first=Brian T.|last=Bolten|date=9 August 2013|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> In Madeira, 30 people were injured when a tent they were in at a church event collapsed on top of them.<ref name="auto1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gendisasters.com/ohio/13208/cincinnati-oh-tornado-aug-1969|title=Cincinnati, OH Tornado, Aug 1969 - GenDisasters ... Genealogy in Tragedy, Disasters, Fires, Floods|website=www.gendisasters.com|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Slam">''Cincinnati Enquirer''. "Tornado Slams Into Cincinnati; 200 Injured, Damage Is Severe". August 10,1969</ref> The most severe damage, all of the deaths, and the majority of injuries, occurred in the area between Hartwell and Golf Manor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QANPLARGXFMC&pg=PA279&lpg=PA279&dq=1969+cincinnati+tornado&source=bl&ots=34fIR3CnnX&sig=-uvkf8duPL333AlHNMXTpMEHhGE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiO0Ib0ieHcAhUpwYMKHZyjBzoQ6AEwE3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=1969+cincinnati+tornado&f=false|title=Thunder in the Heartland: A Chronicle of Outstanding Weather Events in Ohio|first1=Thomas W.|last1=Schmidlin|first2=Jeanne Appelhans|last2=Schmidlin|page=279|date=9 August 1996|publisher=Kent State University Press|via=Google Books|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref><ref name="Slam"/><ref name="noaa.gov"/>
Despite it being among the most significant killer tornadoes in the Cincinnati area, it is considered by some to be one of "Cincinnati's Forgotten Tornadoes" due to several other events in the U.S. in August 1969, including the [[Manson Murders|Manson murders]] (which occurred early that morning) and [[Hurricane Camille]]. In addition, the area was hit by seven significant tornadoes in 1974, 1999 and 2012, including an F4 and an F5 in [[1974 Super Outbreak|1974]] and an F4 in [[Tornado outbreak of April 8–9, 1999|1999]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcpo.com/lifestyle/from-the-vault/from-the-vault-tornadoes-bring-destruction-death-to-tri-state|title=From The Vault: Tornadoes bring destruction, death to Tri-State|first=Greg Noble, WCPO|last=Staff|date=5 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QANPLARGXFMC&pg=PA287&lpg=PA288&dq=1974+cincinnati+tornado&source=bl&ots=34fIR3CnnX&sig=-uvkf8duPL333AlHNMXTpMEHhGE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiO0Ib0ieHcAhUpwYMKHZyjBzoQ6AEwE3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=1974%20cincinnati%20tornado&f=false|title=Thunder in the Heartland: A Chronicle of Outstanding Weather Events in Ohio|first1=Thomas W.|last1=Schmidlin|first2=Jeanne Appelhans|last2=Schmidlin|page=287–288|date=9 August 1996|publisher=Kent State University Press|via=Google Books|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>
