erve/|accessdate=15 May 2018|work=Darlington and Stockton Times|date=15 May 2018}}</ref> |[[West Tanfield]] |[[Hambleton District Council]] |<small>{{coord|54|12|42.3|N|1|34|34.3|W|format=dms|type:landmark|display=inline}}</small> |Nosterfield is a former sand and gravel quarry north east of [[West Tanfield]] and just west of [[Thornborough Henges]]. It was declared in June 2006 and is run by the Lower Ure Conservation Trust (LUCT). The first Bittern recorded in North Yorkshire was at Nosterfield. |<ref>{{cite web|title=Quarries help embattled species {{!}} Mineral and Waste Planning|url=https://www.mineralandwasteplanning.co.uk/quarries-help-embattled-species/article/1446736|website=www.mineralandwasteplanning.co.uk|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=LUCT|url=http://www.luct.org.uk/luct|website=luct.org.uk|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nosterfield LNR|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SiteLNRDetail.aspx?SiteCode=L1009459&SiteName=&countyCode=30&responsiblePerson=&SeaArea=&IFCAArea=|website=designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref> |- |Quarry Moor |[[File:North end of quarry, Quarry Moor, Ripon - geograph.org.uk - 199838.jpg|100px]] |{{convert|9.2|hectare|order=flip}} |[[Ripon]] |[[Harrogate Borough Council]] |<small>{{coord|54|07|11.5|N|1|31|40.5|W|format=dms|type:landmark|display=inline}}</small> |The site was donated to the city in 1945 and designated as an LNR in January 2001. It is of national significance because of its [[Magnesian Limestone|magnesian limestone]] bedrock which allows diverse plants to grow. The site is owned and operated by [[Ripon City Council]]. |<ref>{{cite web|title=Quarry Moor|url=http://www.riponcity.gov.uk/history/quarry-moor/index.html|website=riponcity.gov.uk|accessdate=13 May 2018|date=6 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Quarry Moor LNR|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SiteLNRDetail.aspx?SiteCode=L1009458&SiteName=&countyCode=30&responsiblePerson=&SeaArea=&IFCAArea=|website=designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref> |- |St Nicholas Fields |[[File:Sustrans Route 66 - St. Nicholas Fields - geograph.org.uk - 170032.jpg|100px]] |{{convert|24|acre}} |[[York]] |[[City of York Council]] |<small>{{coord|53|57|27.0|N|1|03|43.1|W|format=dms|type:landmark|display=inline}}</small> |Opened in 2004, St Nicholas Fields was previously the landfill site for the City of York. It stopped receiving waste in 1974 and during the 1980s was subject to a clean-up campaign. It was awarded LNR status in 2004 |<ref>{{cite web|title=Rubbish tip to local nature reserve|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/content/articles/2009/02/27/st_nicholas_field_feature.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=29 April 2018|date=27 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Worsman|first1=Charlotte|title=St Nicholas Fields Local Nature Reserve|url=https://www.york.gov.uk/directory_record/397/st_nicholas_fields_local_nature_reserve|website=www.york.gov.uk|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> |- |The Dell |[[File:Edge Dell - geograph.org.uk - 1425948.jpg|100px]] |{{convert|5.5|hectare|order=flip}} |[[Eastfield, North Yorkshire|Eastfield]], [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]] |[[Scarborough Council]] |<small>{{coord|54|15|36.9|N|0|25|39.7|W|format=dms|type:landmark|display=inline}}</small> |Designated in October 2012, The Dell is an urban fringe that has been adorned with chainsaw sculptures. |<ref>{{cite news|title=Nature reserve statusfor Eastfield ‘gem’|url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/nature-reserve-status-for-eastfield-gem-1-5090273|accessdate=29 April 2018|work=The Scarborough News|date=2 November 2012}}</ref> |- |}
